{"cursor":"16469","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":":\"Pyjama\" redirects here. For other meanings of \"pyjama\" or \"pajama\" or similar\n:see [[Pajamas (disambiguation)]].\n girl, India, in paijama and kurti, 1844.]] 'Pajamas' in US English, spelt\n 'pyjamas' in British English (see also spelling differences), often shortened\n to 'PJs' or 'jammies', can refer to several related types of clothing. The\n original 'pÄijÄma' are loose, lightweight trousers fitted with drawstring\n waistbands and worn in South and West Asia by both sexes. cf. The Oxford\n English Dictionary. 1989 edition. Oxford University Press. Oxford and\n London. In many English-speaking nations (not in India), pajamas are loose-\n fitting, two-piece garments derived from the original garment and worn chiefly\n for sleeping, [http://images.google.com/hosted/life/l?q=%22pajamas%22&imgu-\n rl=074650891e151bf8 \"'Moe' with owners James Davis & wife, in bed in children's\n pajamas, at home.\"], Life magazine, 1971, (Photographer: Ralph Crane).\n but sometimes also for lounging, [http://images.google.com/hosted/life/l?q-\n =%22pajamas%22&imgurl=5f3c2fe401112d79 \"Model clad in lounging pyjamas\n featuring peg-top trousers like jodpurs for sale at Neiman Marcus\"] Life\n magazine, 1939, (Photographer: Alfred Eisenstaedt) also by both sexes. [http://images.google.com/hosted/life/l?q=pajamas&imgurl=2d8884d136c4e6eb\n \"Brazilian composer Heitor Villa-Lobos playing native Brazilian folk instrument\n from his collection, while wearing jacket over his pajamas & smoking cigarette;\n at home.\"] Life magazine, 1945 (Photographer: Unknown; Location: Rio De\n Janeiro) More generally, pajamas may refer to several garments, for both\n daywear and nightwear, derived from traditional pajamas and involving\n variations of style and material.\n\nThe word pyjama or pajama, which originally derives from the Persian word\nÙ¾Ø§ÙØ¬Ø§ÙÙ (pÄyjÄmeh, from pÄy 'leg' and jÄmeh 'garment'), was incorporated into\nthe English language during the British Raj through the Hindustani language (the\nprogenitor language of modern-day Urdu and\nHindi). [http://www.thefreedictionary.com/pajama Dictionary Meaning:\nPajama]; TheFreeDictionary; Free Online Dictionary, Thesaurus, and\nEncyclopedia\n","linknr":631,"url":"Pajamas","recorded":1374546700,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Pajamas&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Pajamas&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Pajamas_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:Muslim_girl_sind1870.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/aa/Muslim_girl_sind1870.jpg/220px-Muslim_girl_sind1870.jpg","/wiki/File:Muslim_girl_sind1870.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Muslim","/wiki/India","/wiki/Kurta","/wiki/American_and_British_English_spelling_differences#Different_spellings_for_different_pronunciations","/wiki/Clothing","/wiki/Trousers","/wiki/Drawstring","/wiki/South_Asia","/wiki/West_Asia","#cite_note-1","/wiki/English_language","/wiki/India","/wiki/Nightwear","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Nightwear","/wiki/Persian_language","/wiki/British_Raj","/wiki/Hindustani_language","/wiki/Urdu","/wiki/Hind